 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub16.ezboard.com/fdruzzilro86846generaldiscussion.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2128.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Hacker got owned!</span><hr size=1> What I have heard happened was that the offender bought an account from someone.  The seller of the account did not tell anyone that he was selling his account and did not de-guild his characters.<br><br>When the offender got on, he pretended that he was the original owner of the account (and knew the guild/characters well enough to be convincing) and got the three players in the same guild as the character he had purchased to give him their passwords for whatever reason.<br><br>He then logged in as the three duped people and stripped any tradable items and auctioned them.  He also deleted no-drop items that he couldn't strip including epics.  Some characters he just deleted outright and created level 1 characters in their place to try to overwrite any backups of the characters to prevent them from being restored.<br><br>Lastly, after all said and done, the offender logged into the guild's website to gloat and admit to what he did.<br><br>Verant had enough to go on to restore the ownership of the three accounts to the original owners and PARTIALLY restore the characters.<br><br>I believe that the revenge &quot;hacker&quot; got enough of the offender's information from guild messageboard registration/ip address tracking, paypal transactions and the auction site registration information that the offender used to sell the items and buy accounts.  Using the &quot;seed&quot; information, he trolled public websites to get the rest of the information he published.  Some of the public information websites that he probably used are fee based, but they legally had the information and were legally dispensing it.  None of this revenge &quot;hacking&quot; was illegal or involved breaking into computer systems.<br><br>If the revenge &quot;hacker&quot; really wanted to, he could have also gotten (probably did and didn't publish it) the last appraised value of the house the accused lives in, the monthy payments, either mortgage or rent, the financial debt/credit load that the parents have, their income information, their place of work, the kid's standardized test scores (not sure about this one), any criminal complaints file by or against them, what vehicle they drive, etc.  There is an assload of info out on the web about anyone who has done any transactions with the government, transactions that are required to be filed with the governement, transactions in areas of businesses that are heavily regulated that routinely trades consumer information all of which may be freely available or available for a fee and is legally available if you know where to look. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#112512><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub16.ezboard.com/bdruzzilro86846.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=arundeltempletn>arundeltempletn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Newbie</span><br>  Posts: 27<br> <font color=#CCCCC8>(2/7/02 5:41:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub16.ezboard.com/fdruzzilro86846generaldiscussion.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2128.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Hacker got owned!</span><hr size=1> That being the case then teher certainly would be civil fraud liability involving the original offender, and quite probably criminal fraud or criminal impersonation liability as well.<br><br>From this data it sounds like the &quot;revenge hacker&quot; may well have violated state and federal laws in obtaining ip addresses. and private information from paid sites, as well as accessing any sites he was not entitled too if they were password protected is also a violation of many state and federal laws.<br><br>As to the mortagge, rent, etc. 